\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6885438 DM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 
Oh I saw - I saw them. Shone their light - they shone their lamp on your face in the bedroom. Well we - we - as I say, we were in - some friends t
he Boys Brigade and we lect-Aig Street - the Boys Brigade and we went down to - do a bit of marching. Of course we all went down Langdale Street. All went down William Henry Street along to Hollow Street through into Fox street and down - into the - the m
arket. The Square Market, Fox Street - Juvenile Street. Well we done all the marching about in there you see. Always done that. And the same - the same applied when we joined the Eighth Irish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10164897 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 Somebody was telling me about when her brother joined the E
ighth Irish. They were in the barracks in 1914 in Shore Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6885438 DM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10164897 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 And they were lifting pints up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6885438 DM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 
Not lifting - well, we - we went - when war broke out we went to Denbigh - no, we didn't go to Denbigh Camp. I went to Cambridge Camp in 1
9 - 1911. Cambridge Camp - down at Cambridge, I was only a boy. I went to Danbigh Camp, North Wales in 1912. I want to Denbigh Camp, Cambridge Camp and - and then - we were at Lancaster - Lancaster when war broke out. 1914. And - just get - we were all se
t
tled down in the camp and we got dished out with our blankets, our bowls for the tents and then when we got there, put them all in. I want to go and meet Archie Kemp. I went to meet Archie Kemp 'cos he - they were there - all the Lancs - all the Lancs bat
t
alions were there and I went and - into the YMCA with Archie Kemp. Well while we were in there - said that - war broke out. Well we had to get back to our own billets again. And we got back to our own - tents down - everything all down, all packed up - ev
e
rything all away and we left there then at about twelve or one o'clock - assembled again. Onto the train again and brought back to Liverpool here, and we got put in our own - whatsnames - our own - barracks. Corner of - top of William Henry Street and - S
h
ore Street. Well that's where we were - in there. And we were in there and all the crowds of people were thousands of people outside, wanting to know about getting home, about all the rest of it and what are we going to do. Well - while we - while we were
 
in there through the windows they were putting - putting a rope down, tying a basket on with beer - bottles of beer and sandwiches and things up through the window - we're not getting out and then it come about later with find - trying to find this here h
o
ard - some coke and one thing and another, but it come about later on about - nine o'clock - eight o'clock or nine o'clock at night to say - as - single men - single men can go home now and he back again for twelve o'clock. At the barracks. Back again to 
the barracks. You had to give your word of honour you had to be back again or M.P. round your house. To be back again at twelve o'clock at night and the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3738228 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118  men can go from twelve o'clock until the next morning. And that was our the following day then o
ff we went down to - the lines of communication down - we had Southampton. Or Winsfield - Fleet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10164897 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 Did you go right over to France?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6885438 DM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 
No. Oh no, we went from there - we went to Sevenoaks - Sevenoaks, Canterbury - Canterbury to Whitstable, battalion 
arrived there for about three or four months and then - officers servant then over there. We were at Sandich Bay, Walmer, Deal - and then - we went out with the Fifty-first Ireland Division. Fifty - then we come - we got brought from there again and come 
right home and right up to Mowsley - Lark Lane Estate, Mowsley. And from Lord Derby Estate they asked them all in the - everybody - willing to go out to France, yes, well they said there's the Fifty-first Highland Division going out }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15741537\charrsid474118 there}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118  and this Colonel N
eal said, don't think you're going out to a picnic. Well we were all keen for going you know. Don't think you'll have a picnic - I've had one battalion cut up now. I - and he was pretty old two - he was about fifty odd then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10164897 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 How long were you in France then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6885438 DM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 Four years and ten months. Oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10164897 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 Did you get wounded at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6885438 DM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 No. And was on - on the - on the Cycle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15741537\charrsid474118  - Cycle Battalion}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118  and then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10164897 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 You were lucky weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6885438 DM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 Oh aye, we were very lucky, there's no doubt about it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10164897 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 Don Barrett got wounded didn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6885438 DM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 
Don Barrett got wounded, yes. And Don Barrett wasn't out there as long as I was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10164897 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 Archie Kemp go the Military Medal didn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6885438 DM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 Archie Kemp got the - the Double M.M. too. I think so - double M M. He sh
ould have got the D.C.M. Archie though - from what I heard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10164897 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 He's a nice fellow Archie Kemp?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6885438 DM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 
His old fellow - before his old fellow died he said to me, he said - look here Dan, he says, will you and Archie still keep - still be pals? I said, yes, all right. I was home when Archies father died. Home on leave.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10164897 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6913383\charrsid474118 Archies a nice fellow isn't he?
